{
  "doc_id": "40381",
  "text": "ROS are known to participate in the development of many cardiovascular diseases. [CITATION_1] In VSMCs, various stimuli can induce the production of ROS, which might induce further proliferation, [CITATION_2] increase inflammatory gene expression [CITATION_3] and modulate matrix remodeling. [CITATION_4] In endothelial cells, ROS can regulate the expression of adhesion molecules, including vascular cell adhesion molecule-1 and intracellular adhesion molecule-1. [CITATION_5] The production of ROS, which can represent a second messenger, can trigger a series of downstream signal transduction pathways, such as those mediated by Akt 22 or ERK1/2. [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] A weakened antioxidative defense system and oxidative stress can contribute to the dysfunction of vascular cells, increasing the relative inflammatory gene expression. [CITATION_8] Based on the effect of ROS on VSMCs and endothelial cells, ROS can participate in the pathogenesis of atherosclerosis. Our study showed that prorenin can promote the production of ROS through PRR independently of AngII. In HEK 14 and neuronal [CITATION_9] cells, ROS are also involved in prorenininduced effects through PRR. In addition, the expression of PRR is regulated by ROS in diabetic rats. [CITATION_10] In previous studies, the prorenin-induced phosphorylation of ERK1/2 has been shown in VSMCs. [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] Our study further confirmed that the prorenin-induced phosphorylation of ERK1/2 is mediated by ROS production, and that the inhibition of ROS production reduced the phosphorylation of ERK1/2. Early studies have also reported that ROS can mediate ERK1/2 phosphorylation in response to AngII. [CITATION_14] A recent study claimed that in neuronal cells, the production of ROS through PRR is regulated by ERK1/2 and PI3K/Akt. [CITATION_15] There may be a crosstalk between ROS production and the phosphorylation of ERK1/2, which remains to be elucidated. Overall, ROS and ERK1/2 play pivotal roles in terms of prorenin-induced effects.",
